> Also, we should make this be a normal method and not a static method (since the session is already bound to the object).

I'm not really sure that this will work as my session is of type 'terminal_server'. That is why I created static method in the first place. If I changed *autodetect* method to a class method I will end up by calling the autodetect of my TerminalServer class or will need to create a new object for each subclass (IOS, NXOS, Huawei,...).

By doing this way I only create one single basic SSH session (terminal_server). Basically when I iterate over the SSH_MAPPER_BASE items, these are just class and not object so I cannot call a class method at this point or I will need to instantiate one new object per items in the for loop. This will end with a SSH connection per item.

```python
       for k, v in SSH_MAPPER_BASE.items():
             try:
                 accuracy = v.autodetect(self.connection)
                 self.potential_matches[k] = accuracy
             except:
                 pass
```

> I would also vote, we don't do a bare except so at a minimum except Exception (or better would be to specify the exceptions we are looking for. Note, it is probably better to get some exceptions here (otherwise we are probably hiding errors by autodetect just returning 0).

This could be easily changed to catch *Exception*. For now as used a global Exception as I don't really know what the function could raise.

> So I would think the definition of autodetect in base_connection.py should be 
def autodetect(self, matches, default_priority=99):

I thought of using this method definition in the first place. However I wanted to keep this autodetect as generic as possible and let anybody use their own logic to implement the detection. If for some reason, someone prefer to use something different than matching some strings, he would be able to do so (reading the SSH banner, capturing an SSH footprint or whatever).

