@georgh0021 since, as you said, turnover defaults to average=True, then the last case in your list of "average=False" should actually be in in the "average=True" list.

This means the only cases where average=False is used is in the first two cases you list, which is used for adjusting returns for slippage. This, I believe, is actually the correct usage here because we are using the turnover here to capture our dollars lost due to slippage; we should not be cutting it in half.

I believe, therefore, that our current implementation is consistent - but @twiecki can confirm. Whether or not we choose to use average=True or average=False for everything is a separate issue.

```python
from functools import total_ordering
@total_ordering
class Path(object):
    def eval(self, graph, subj=None, obj=None):
        raise NotImplementedError()

    def __eq__(self, other):
        if not isinstance(other, Path):
            raise TypeError('incomparable types: %s() == %s()' % (
                repr(self), repr(other)))
        return repr(self) == repr(other)

    def __lt__(self, other):
        if not isinstance(other, Path):
            raise TypeError('unorderable types: %s() < %s()' % (
                repr(self), repr(other)))
        return repr(self) < repr(other)
```
