Let's say our function is

```python
def f(x):
  for i in range(N):
    x = np.sin(x)
  return np.sum(x)
```

Evaluating `f(x)` or `jacobian_vector_product(f)(x)(v)` requires memory that is independent of `N`, since even though we allocate temporaries for intermediate outputs, we can also free them up as we go. I agree that evaluating the JVP requires about twice the max memory as evaluating the function, since we basically need two temporaries in the JVP for each place we needed one temporary in the function, but both are independent of `N`.

However, when we trace the execution of `f(x)` to evaluate `grad(f)(x)` in reverse-mode, we need to store all the intermediates in the trace, requiring an amount of memory that grows linearly in `N`. That memory usage, which scales with `N`, is the unit of measure when we compare how much memory an HVP takes compared to the memory required by the reverse-mode gradient.

I think the rev-rev HVP requires memory that scales like `2N`, while the fwd-rev HVP requires memory that scales like `N`.

I think the approach you've taken here is fine. I may still like the approach I advocated [here](https://github.com/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/issues/2456#issuecomment-186364711) slightly better, but your approach avoids this [problem](http://cdn.meme.am/instances/500x/56732810.jpg).

I also struggled with testing this. In the end, I used trivial examples such as the ones suggested [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/20722064/can-a-shell-script-delete-or-overwrite-itself) instead of running `letsencrypt-auto` directly. I did find though that `mv -f` successfully fixed the problem.

