@jasongrout and @maartenbreddels OK, so I believe this is ready to go.

One thing I don't *love* about this implementation is that because ipython/traitlets#451 is unresolved, we're stuck between choosing to force `value` to be `Bytes` on input to the constructor (in which case if you have a URL that is some unicode object, you must decode it before passing it to `value`), or erroneously setting it as a `Union[Bytes,Unicode]` trait (or something like that).

I think having a dedicated `from_url` parameter that accepts `unicode` is the best compromise until traitlets has support for a preprocessor hook.

@kirill888 & @woodcockr, I agree with both of you but on different levels.

@kirill888, I believe is talking about the lower level eager dc.load() on a single instance/node. This is required no matter how you look at it. At some point in the dc.load() chain, it needs to load data into memory on a single instance, hence the utility of PR.
@woodcockr is perhaps? talking about a higher level Module/API that handles a load & compute over multiple instances. This will still need the lower level single instance dc.load() per instance. Perhaps another PR?

Knowing how many bytes of memory a dc.load would consume for a single instance would be good. The Module/API @woodcockr is talking about could use this information to determine the total usage per instance and thus, across multiple instances. The ODC Execution Engine is designed in a such a way that plays nice with this. It's good to know the overall usage, but it's more important to know whether each per instance dc.load() fits in local memory.

Back on topic:
@Kirill888, this is a great idea. This has always been at the back of my mind, but never found the time.

This shouldn't be hard to do:

The min size in bytes required would be (sources.shape) * (geobox.shape) * (sizeof(dtype)) * number_of_bands + metadata_size. More of wrapped as a python numpy array or a xarray dataset/dataarray.

Of course, this is the lower bound due to potential driver inefficiencies.

A shared memory array could be used to reduce the overhead in the creation of temporary arrays and concurrent IO.

The S3 driver does some of this, but not perfectly. It has enough indexed metadata to work out how much IO and pixels is required for a given dc.load.

A alternative way for dc.load() to operate: **Load into a shared memory array on disk**. Still, knowing how many bytes required is beneficial.

